[2026-04-12]
CATEGORY: ENV_PARITY
SERVICE: cross-cutting (local dev / poc)
TASK: POC1 smoke test — verify parser imports work before running LLM build step
SYMPTOM: `source .venv/bin/activate && python -c "import vertexai"` → ModuleNotFoundError.
         `.venv/bin/python -c "import vertexai"` → same. `python3 -c "import vertexai"` → works.
ROOT_CAUSE: google-cloud-aiplatform (and therefore vertexai) is installed at user level
            (~/.local/lib/python3.12/site-packages) via a bare `pip install`, not into the
            project's .venv. The venv is isolated — it does not inherit user site-packages.
            Bare `python3` picks up ~/.local; venv python does not.
PREVENTED_BY: Before writing run instructions for any script, run
            `pip show <package> | grep Location`. If Location is ~/.local/..., the package
            is user-level and venv python will not find it. Either install into the venv
            or document that bare `python3` must be used. A startup assertion
            (`python3 -c "import vertexai"`) in the POC README would surface this
            immediately rather than mid-way through a smoke test.
SOLUTION: Use bare `python3` (not `.venv/bin/python`) for all poc/ scripts.
          Updated poc/README.md and SESSION.md next-session instructions accordingly.
DEAD_ENDS: `source .venv/bin/activate && python` — venv isolation excludes user site-packages.
           `.venv/bin/python` — same isolation, same failure.

